<p>I know that the rem css unit is a relative unit which is used to derive font sizes from the root element i.e html.</p>  <p>My question is- how are length based css properties like width, height, padding, margin, if specified in rem - for any element derived from the html element.</p>  <p>As an example:</p>  <pre><code>&lt;html class="basicStyle"&gt; &lt;body&gt;  &lt;div id="view"&gt;This is some content&lt;/div&gt; &lt;/body&gt; &lt;/html&gt; </code></pre>  <p>Style:</p>  <pre><code>.basicStyle{width:500px; font-size:20px} #view{width:3rem; font-size:2rem} </code></pre>  <p>If I try this out in chrome, the width of the #view div should be 3*500px = 1500px - However it is not so.</p>  <p>I want to know if we specify the width or padding of an element in rem - from which element and how is it calculated - to get the computed width.</p>  <p>Any documentation is welcome too.</p>  <p>Thanks.</p>